#week-title("Four", "The Twelve Principles & The Mineral Seed")

=== Core Teaching

The final stage of the Archaeus work is the subdivision of each element into its
three principles (Mercury, Sulphur, Salt). This yields *twelve distinct
fractions* — the "coding languages" of the universe.

The alchemist then acts as a programmer, mixing specific ratios of these twelve
fractions to direct the Gur toward a particular mineral expression. Through many
cycles of *imbibition* (moistening) and drying, the Gur gradually become heavy,
gritty, and sandy — arriving at a stable mineral character.

#doctrine[
  _"When the Gur crystallises into mineral structures not originally present in
  the water, the Universal Seed has been determined. This is the starting point
  for the metallic work."_
  #align(right)[— TTAO curriculum]
]

=== Practical Protocol: IV & V

+ *The 4x3 Distillation:* Sub-divide each of the four elemental fractions into
  three equal parts by volatility: Sulphur (Soul), Mercury (Spirit), and Salt
  (Body). Label every fraction precisely.
+ *Recombination:* Combine the twelve fractions in specific ratios (Method A:
  Principles united; Method B: Elements united).
+ *Imbibition:* Moisten the dried Gur with the combined preparation and dry
  again. Repeat until the *Peacock's Tail* of iridescent change appears.
+ *Fixation:* Digest the sealed flask at higher temperatures (up to 90°C) to
  fix the mineral seed.

=== Topics This Week

- The Twelve Principles and their distinct properties
- Imbibition cycles: the feeding of the Gur
- The Peacock's Tail: iridescent signs of mineral determination
- Determining the Universal Seed for Year Three

